{"title_page": "List of shipwrecks in January 1863", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe '''list of shipwrecks in January 1863''' includes ships sunk, foundered, grounded, or otherwise lost during January [[1863]].\n{{Dynamic list}}\n{{Calendar ToC}}\n\n==1 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=1 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Carmen''\n|flag={{flag|Chile}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] foundered in the [[Pacific Ocean]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Coquimbo]] to [[Lota, Chile|Lota]].<ref name=Times020363a>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The West India, Pacific, and Mexican Mails |date=2 March 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24495 |column=C-D }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[CS Neptune|CS ''Neptune'']] (or&nbsp;CSS&nbsp;''Neptune Camp'')\n|flag={{army|Confederate States of America|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Battle of Galveston]]: The armed [[cottonclad]] [[Tugboat|tug]] was sunk by [[United States Navy]] warships in Galveston Harbor off [[Galveston, Texas]], when a shell passed through her [[Hull (ship)|hull]]. She suffered eight killed and 20 wounded, and three of the wounded later died of their injuries.<ref name=gainesp171>Gaines, p. 171.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Nova Scotian''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Colombo]], [[Ceylon]]. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=Times050163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Westfield|1861|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War, Battle of Galvesto]: The armed sidewheel [[paddle steamer]], serving as [[flagship]] of the naval squadron [[Union blockade|blockading]] Galveston, ran aground on a [[sandbar]] in Galveston Harbor off Galveston, while in action with the [[gunboat]] [[CS Bayou City|CS ''Bayou City'']] and the armed [[tugboat]] [[CS Neptune|CS ''Neptune'']] (both {{army|Confederate States of America|1861}}). She was blown up to prevent her capture by [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] forces, killing the fleet commander, [[Commander (United States)|Commander]] [[William B. Renshaw]], and several members of her crew when the explosives detonated sooner than they expected.<ref name=\"gainesp172\">Gaines, p. 172.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==2 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=2 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Arnoldi'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[cutter (ship)|cutter]] ran aground on the Middle Sand, off the north [[Kent]] coast. She was refloated and towed in to [[Whitstable]] in a severely leaky condition.<ref name=LM050163>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=5 January 1863 |issue=4650 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Gratitude'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on the Newcombe Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Suffolk]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=S050163>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=5 January 1863 |issue=11981 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Louisa''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Braunton]], [[Devon]] with the loss of one of her eight crew. Survivors were rescued by the Braunton Lifeboat. She was on a voyage from [[Appledore, Torridge|Appledore]], Devon to [[Newport, Monmouthshire]].<ref name=Times030163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=3 January 1863 |page_number=9 |issue=24446 |column=B }}</ref><ref name=Times050163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=5 January 1863 |page_number=11 |issue=24447 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Marie Amelie''\n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the Longsand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Essex]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] with the loss of three of her crew. She was on a voyage from [[Grimsby]], [[Lincolnshire]], United Kingdom to [[Bordeaux]], [[Gironde]].<ref name=Times050163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ripple'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore near [[Chipiona]], Spain. She was on a voyage from [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]] to [[Seville]], Spain. She was refloated the next day and taken in to Seville, where she was condemned.<ref name=S100163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Dantsic''\n|flag=[[File:Gdansk flag.svg|22px]] [[Danzig|Dantsic]] \n|desc=The ship foundered in the [[North Sea]]. All five people on board were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[London]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] to Dantsic.<ref name=Times080163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Neuha'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[ketch]] ran aground on the Abertay Bank, at the mouth of the [[River Tay]] and sank. Her crew were rescued by the Broughty Ferry and Buddonness Lifeboats. She was on a voyage from [[North Shields]], [[Northumberland]] to [[Dundee]], [[Forfarshire]].<ref name=DC050163>{{Cite news |title=Vessel Wrecked in the River |newspaper=Dundee Courier |location=Dundee |date=5 January 1863 |issue=2934 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Time and Truth''\n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[Victoria (Australia)]]\n|desc=The [[barque]] carrying 2,600 sheep, was approaching [[Bluff, New Zealand|Bluff]], New Zealand from Melbourne when a heavy gale sprang up. The captain attempted to take the ship into Bluff Harbour, but it was struck by a swell and pushed into rocks off [[Stirling Point]]. The [[steamship|steamer]] ''Aphrasis'' succeeding in rescuing the crew and about 500 sheep before the ''Time and Truth'' went under. While returning to Bluff, the ''Aphrasis'' herself was involved in a collision with the steamer ''Prince Alfred'' and was heavily damaged.<ref name=SNZD8384>Ingram & Wheatley, pp. 83\u201384.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lady Mary Stewart'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship struck the Garrick Rock, in the [[Irish Sea]]. She was on a voyage from [[Runcorn]], [[Cheshire]] to [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]]. She put in to [[Port St. Mary]], [[Isle of Man]] in a leaky condition.<ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pax'' \n|flag={{flag|Hamburg|admiralty}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore near \"Kjaergaard\", Denmark. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Rostock]] to [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]].<ref name=S100163/><ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==5 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=5 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Iceni''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was destroyed by fire at sea. Her crew were rescued by ''Yorkshire'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=Times230163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Prosperity'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[sloop]] ran aground on the Longsand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Essex]]. She was on a voyage from [[Dunkerque]], [[Nord (departements)|Nord]] to [[London]]. She was refloated and assisted in to [[Harwich]], Essed.<ref name=Benham/><ref name=S080163>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=8 January 1863 |issue=11984 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==6 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Balmoral'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground off Whiteforeland Point, [[Renfrewshire]]. She was on a voyage from [[Glasgow]], Renfrewshire to the [[West Indies]]. She was refloated and towed back to Glasgow.<ref name=S130163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Batallion'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] was driven ashore at [[Sunderland, County Durham]]. She was on a voyage from [[Bordeaux]], [[Gironde]] to Sunderland. She was refloated and taken in to port.<ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Esteburg'' \n|flag={{flag|Hamburg|admiralty}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Eyemouth]], [[Berwickshire]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was on a voyage from [[Rye, Sussex]] to [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]], United Kingdom. She was refloated and taken in to Eyemouth in a severely damaged condition.<ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jacob Musselman''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The 144-ton [[Paddle steamer|sternwheel]] [[Troop transport|transport]] was captured by troops of the [[Arkansas Cavalry Company]] ({{army|Confederate States of America|1861}}) on the [[Mississippi River]] opposite [[Memphis, Tennessee]], [[Confederate States of America]]. The [[Confederate States Army]] took her 15 miles (24 km) upstream to [[Bradley's Landing]], [[Arkansas]], where they removed her cargo and burned her.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJanJun1863>[http://www.usnlp.org/navychronology/1863a.html usnlp.org Navy Chronology of the Civil War, January-June 1863]</ref><ref name=gainesp97>Gaines, p. 97.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sally'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] ran around and was wrecked at [[Bilbao|Bilboa]], Spain. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to Bilboa.<ref name=S140163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unidentified flatboat\n|flag=Unknown\n|desc=American Civil War: The [[flatboat]] was burned by 