ed and taken in to [[Cowes]], Isle of Wight in a leaky condition.<ref name=S100163>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=10 January 1863 |issue=11986 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pride of the West''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was wrecked on the Dulas Rocks, on the coast of [[Anglesey]]. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Montevideo]], Uruguay.<ref name=Times100163a>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=10 January 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24452 |column=E }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ridesdale''<!--per majority of sources-->\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]], under tow of the [[tugboat|tug]] ''Aid'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) was run into by the [[steamship]] {{SS|Ceylon|1858|2}} ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and sank in [[Southampton Water]] off [[Calshot Castle]], [[Hampshire]] One person on board each vessel was killed. ''Ridesdale'' was on a voyage from [[Southampton]], Hampshire to the [[West Indies]]. Her crew were rescued by ''Aid''.<ref name=Times100163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Fatal Collision |date=10 January 1863 |page_number=9 |issue=24452 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=Times120163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Fatal Collision in Southampton Water |date=12 January 1863 |page_number=11 |issue=24463 |column=D }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sparkling Sea''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: Carrying 70 men of the 25th [[Artillery battery|Battery]], [[New York Light Artillery]], and 106 horses, the [[Troop transport|transport]] ran aground without loss of life off the coast of on [[Ajax Reef]], about {{convert|10|nmi|km}} from the [[Carysfort Reef Light]]house, [[Florida]], [[Confederate States of America]]. The [[gunboat]] {{USS|Sagamore|1861|6}} ({{navy|United States|1861}}) removed the horses and some stores. By 18 January, ''Sparkling Sea'' was a total wreck.<ref>Gaines, pp. 44-45.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n<!--\n==10 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=10 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}-->\n\n==11 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=11 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Adler'' \n|flag=Flag unknown\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore near [[dungeness (headland)|Dungeness]], [[Kent]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was refloated the next day and taken in to [[Dover]], Kent.<ref name=S140163>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=14 January 1863 |issue=11989 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Grampus No. 2''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: Carrying a cargo of [[coal]] and towing five coal [[barge]]s, the 352-ton armed [[paddle steamer]] was captured on the [[Mississippi River]] just off the [[wharf]] at [[Memphis, Tennessee]], [[Confederate States of America]] by troops of the [[Arkansas Cavalry Company]] ({{army|Confederate States of America|1863}}). The [[Confederate States Army|Confederates]] ran her five miles upriver to [[Mound City, Arkansas]], with the barges, where they set her on fire and cast her adrift on the Mississippi, and she and the barges sank.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJanJun1863/><ref name=gainesp96>Gaines, p. 96.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Haidee''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship departed from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] for [[Harbour Grace]], [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]], [[British North America]]. No furthert trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=Times230663>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=23 June 1863 |page_number=9 |issue=24592 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Hatteras|1861|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[File:USS Hatteras sinking.jpg|thumb|Nineteenth-century illustration of USS&nbsp;''Hatteras''&nbsp;(right) sinking under fire from CSS&nbsp;''Alabama''&nbsp;(left).]]American Civil War, [[CSS Alabama's Gulf of Mexico Expeditionary Raid]], [[Action off Galveston Light]]: The [[gunboat]], a sidewheel [[paddle steamer]], was sunk in combat with the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Alabama|CSS ''Alabama'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America|1861}}) in the [[Gulf of Mexico]] off [[Galveston, Texas]], Confederate States of America with the loss of two lives. ''Alabama'' took her 118 survivors prisoner.<ref>Gaines, pp. 168-169.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Margaret and Elizabeth'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] ran aground off the coast of [[Nord (departements)|Nord]], France. She was on a voyage from [[Newport, Monmouthshire]] to [[Dunkerque]], Nord. She was refloated and taken in to Dunkerque.<ref name=S140163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==12 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=12 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Akbar''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked at \"Rietveld\", [[British Cape Colony|Cape Colony]].<ref name=Times020363>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Cape of Good Hope |date=2 March 1863 |page_number=10 |issue=24495 |column=D }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Edith'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship sprang a leak and was beached at [[Grimsby]], [[Lincolnshire]]. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[Rochester, Kent]].<ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Emily'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] sprang a leak and was beached at Grimsby. She was on a voyage from Sunderland to Rochester.<ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Henrietta'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on the Gunfleet Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Suffolk]]. She was on a voyage from [[Hartlepool]], [[County Durham]] to [[London]]. She was refloated with the assistance of four [[smack (ship)|smacks]] and assisted in to Harwich in a severely leaky condition.<ref name=Benham/><ref name=S140163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lucy'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground in the [[Solent]]. She was on a voyage from Sunderland to [[Oporto]], Portugal. She was refloated and put in to [[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]].<ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==13 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=13 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Charter''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The 114-ton sternwheel [[paddle steamer]] was burned by troops of the [[cavalry]] [[brigade]] of [[Major general|Major General]] [[Joseph Wheeler]] ({{army|Confederate States of America|1863}}) on the [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]], side of the [[Cumberland River]] 5 miles (8 km) from [[Harpeth Shoals]].<ref name=gainesp159>Gaines, p. 159.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mauney'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on the Holm Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Suffolk]]. She was on a voyage from [[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]] to [[Sunderland, County Durham]]. She was refloated and taken in to [[Lowestoft]], Suffolk.<ref name=S140163/><ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pelican'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] was driven ashore at [[Waterloo, Lancashire]]. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Cork (city)|Cork]].<ref name=S140163/> She was later refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=LM160163>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=16 January 1863 |issue=4660 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Trio''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War: Carrying 400 wounded [[Union Army]] troops and a cargo of [[cotton]], the 150-ton [[Paddle steamer|sternwheel]] [[Hospital ship|hospital steamer]] was captured and burned by troops of the [[cavalry]] [[brigade]] of [[Major general|Major General]] [[Joseph Wheeler]] ({{army|Confederate States of America|1863}}) on the [[Nashville, Tennessee]], [[Confederate States of America]], side of the [[Cumberland River]] {{convert|5|nmi|km}} from [[Harpeth Shoals]].<ref name=gainesp162>Gaines, p. 162.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''W. H. Slidell''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War: The armed [[tinclad]] [[Steamship|steamer]] was captured and burned by troops of the [[cavalry]] [[brigade]] of [[Major general|Major General]] [[Joseph Wheeler]] ({{army|Confederate States of America|1863}}) on the Nashville side of the Cumberland River {{convert|5|nmi|km}} from Harpeth Shoals.<ref name=gainesp164>Gaines, p. 164.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==14 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=14 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Columbia|1862|6}}\n|flag={{navy|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: The armed [[screw steamer]] ran aground at [[Masonboro Inlet]], [[North Carolina]], [[Confederate States of America]]. After a [[gale]] struck on 15 January, the gunboat {{USS|Penobscot|1861|6}} ({{navy|United States|1861}}) rescued 30 men from the wreck during the storm on 15\u201316 January before Confederate [[artillery]] drove her off. Confederate forces captured the wreck on 17 January and burned it.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJanJun1863/><ref name=Gainesp116>Gaines, p.116</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Earl of Derby'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship caught fire in [[Lough Foyle]] and was scuttled.<ref name=LM150163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Parthonia''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War: The 261-ton sternwheel [[paddle steamer]] was burned by [[Confederate States Army]] troops on the [[Cumberland River]] in [[Tennessee]], Confederate States of America. They had captured her on the river the previous day at the head of [[Harpeth Shoals]].<ref name=gainesp162>Gaines, p. 162.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pioneer''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on a reef off the Karren Islands, [[Netherlands East Indies]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Manila]], [[Spanish East Indies]] to [[London]].<ref name=Times180263>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=18 February 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24485 |column=A }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rose'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was wrecked on the Villez Martin Rocks, on the coast of [[Loire-Inf\u00e9rieure]]. She was on a voyage from [[Dunkerque]], [[Nord (departements)|Nord]] to [[Nantes]], Loire-Inf\u00e9rieure.<ref name=S200163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==15 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=15 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Dashaway''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore {{convert|20|nmi|km}} north east of [[Cape May]], [[New Jersey]]. She was on a voyage from [[Messina]], [[Sicily]], [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]] to [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=Times040263>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=4 February 1863 |page_number=5 |issue=24473 |column=E }}</ref>\n}}<!--Enterprise not ashore at Mockbeggar on this date-->\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Iron Duke'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] was driven ashore at [[Mockbeggar, Cheshire]].<ref name=LM200163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[CSS J. A. Cotton|CSS ''J. A. Cotton'']]\n|flag={{navy|Confederate States of America|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The [[Paddle steamer|sidewheel]] partial [[Ironclad warship|ironclad]] [[gunboat]] was [[Scuttling|scuttled]] and burned by her crew in [[Bayou Teche]] off [[Brashear City, Louisiana|Brashear City]], [[Louisiana]], to serve as a [[blockship]] and to prevent her capture by [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] forces after she was badly damaged in combat with [[United States Navy]] gunboats.<ref>[https://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/confederate_ships/j-a-cotton.html Naval History and Heritage Command: Confederate Ships: J. A. Cotton]</ref><ref name=gainesp67>Gaines, p. 67.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''M\u00e8re de Famille''\n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The ship was run down and sunk in the [[English Channel]] off [[Portland Dorset]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] by ''Turk'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). Her crew were rescued by ''Turk''.<ref name=Times190163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rosebud'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the Barrow Sand, in the North Sea off the coast of Essex. Her five crew were rescued by the [[smack (ship)|smack]] ''Alarm'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Rosebud'' was on a voyage from [[Gothenburg]], Sweden to [[London]].<ref name=Benham/><ref name=DC190163>{{Cite news |title=Dundee Shipping |newspaper=Dundee Courier |location=Dundee |date=19 January 1863 |issue=2946 }}</ref> She was refloated and taken in to [[Sheerness]], [[Kent]] in a sinking condition.<ref name=DC200163>{{Cite news |title=Dundee Shipping |newspaper=Dundee Courier |location=Dundee |date=20 January 1863 |issue=2947 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==16 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=16 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Alma''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship exploded in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] with the loss of all hands. She was on a voyage from [[Licata]], [[Sicily]], [[Kingdom of Italy|Itlay]] to [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]].<ref name=Times180263/>\n}}\n{{