 January 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24461 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=Times220163a/><ref name=DN200163/><ref name=LM210163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mudlark'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The unmanned [[dredger]] sank in a [[squall]] at [[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]].<ref name=DN200163>{{Cite news |title=Severe Gale |newspaper=Daily News |location=London |date=20 January 1863 |issue=5211 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Naples Packet''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[collier (ship)|collier]] collided with ''George Hughes'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and was abandoned in the [[North Sea]] off [[Aldeburgh]], [[Suffolk]]. She was on a voyage from [[South Shields]], [[County Durham]] to [[Rochester, Kent]].<ref name=Times220163/><ref name=Times220163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sabrina''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at Horse Head, [[County Cork]]. She was on a voyage from [[Cork (city)|Cork]] to [[Bristol]], [[Gloucestershire]].<ref name=Times240163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sea Swallow''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] foundered in the North Sea off the coast of [[Norfolk]] with the loss of four of her seven crew. Survivors were rescued by the Yarmouth Lifeboat.<ref name=Times220163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Transit''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore near [[Whitehaven]], [[Cumberland]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Dublin]] to Whitehaven.<ref name=Times220163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Twins''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground and sank at [[Barnstaple]], [[Devon]]. She was on a voyage from Dublin to [[Antwerp]], Belgium. She was refloated the next day and taken in to Barnstaple in a severely damaged condition.<ref name=Times240163/>/\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unnamed\n|flag=Flag unknown\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the [[Tuskar Rock, Ireland|Tuskar Rock]] with the loss of all hands<ref name=Times220163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==21 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=21 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Admiral''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground at [[Leasowe]], [[Cheshire]] and sank. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Bombay]], [[British Raj|India]].<ref name=Times220163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Agnes''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was severely damaged at [[Fleetwood]], [[Lancashire]].<ref name=Times220163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Alma''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship sank in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] off [[Sicily]], [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Licata]], Sicily to [[Falmouth, Cornwall]].<ref name=Times240163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Cabriole''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was severely damaged at Fleetwood.<ref name=Times220163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''James Riddle''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore on the [[Mull of Galloway]], [[Wigtownshire]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt Eyalet|Egypt]] to the [[River Clyde|Clyde]].<ref name=Times230163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jane Storer''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[full-rigged ship]] was driven ashore and wrecked near [[Waterloo, Lancashire]] with the loss of two of her seventeen crew. She was on a voyage from [[Portland, Maine]] to [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]].<ref name=Times220163a/><ref name=Times310163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''John H. Elliott''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The [[full-rigged ship]] ran aground on the Burbo Bank and broke her back. Her crew were rescued by the [[tugboat|tug]] ''Reliance'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''John H. Elliott''' was on a voyage from Liverpool to [[New York City|New York]].<ref name=Times220163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=22 January 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24462 |column=C }}</ref><ref name=Times220163a/><ref name=DN200163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Kezia''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Great Yarmouth]], [[Norfolk]]. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[Caen]], [[Calvados (department)|Calvados]], France.<ref name=Times220163a>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Gale |date=22 January 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24462 |column=E }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lady Vaughan''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the North Sea {{convert|21|nmi|km}} off [[Ostend]], [[West Flanders]], Belgium. Her crew were rescued by a Belgian fishing vessel. She was on a voyage from Sunderland to [[Saint-Malo]], [[Ille-et-Vilaine]], France.<ref name=Times290163a>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=29 January 1863 |page_number=11 |issue=24468 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Liberty''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: After breaking loose from her moorings at [[Cornfield Harbor, Maryland]], and drifting into the [[Coan River]] in [[Virginia]], [[Confederate States of America]], the [[barge]] was captured and burned in the Coan River by Confederates aboard the captured barge ''J. C. Davis'' ({{flag|United States|1861}}).<ref name=gainesp184>Gaines, p. 184.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Nazarine''\n|flag={{flagicon|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was driven ashore and severely damaged at [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was on a voyage from Cardiff to New York.<ref name=Times230163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Gale |date=23 January 1863 |page_number=7 |issue=24463 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=Times240163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Norval''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in the North Sea off [[Lowestoft]], [[Suffolk]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]] to [[London]].<ref name=Times310163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pride of Canada''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at the mouth of the [[River Mersey]]. Sje was on a voyage from [[Benin City|Benin]], Africa to Liverpool.<ref name=Times220163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pulla''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the North Sea. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Hartlepool]], [[County Durham]] to [[London]].<ref name=Times230163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Punch''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven from her moorings, holed by her anchor, and sank at Fleetwood. She was on a voyage from [[Newry]], [[County Antrim]] to Fleetwood.<ref name=Times220163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rubin''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] ran aground on the Salthouse Bank, in the [[Irish Sea]]] off the coast of Lancashire. Her crew were rescued by the Lytham Lifeboat. ''Rubin'' was on a voyage from \"Woodpoint\" to [[Glasson Dock]], Lancashire. She subsequently floated off and was wrecked on the Horse Bank.<ref name=Times220163/><ref name=Times220163a/><ref name=Times230163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Spinner''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Formby]], Lancashire. She was on a voyage from [[Sagua la Grande]], [[Captaincy General of Cuba|Cuba]] to the [[River Clyde|Clyde]].<ref name=Times230163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Unity''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was discovered derelict off [[Margate]], [[Kent]]. She was taken in to Margate.<ref name=Times220163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Wilhelmina''\n|flag={{flag|Netherlands}}\n|desc=The ship was drive ashore on [[Vlieland]], [[Friesland]] with the loss of two of her crew. She was on a voyage from [[Groningen (city)|Groningen]] to London.<ref name=Times240163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unidentified schooner\n|flag=Unknown\n|desc=American Civil War, Union blockade: The [[schooner]], a [[Blockade runners of the American Civil War|blockade runner]] heavily laden with supplies, was forced aground at [[New Topsail Inlet]] or [[Stump Inlet]] (sources disagree) on the coast of [[North Carolina]], Confederate States of Ameriac by the armed [[screw steamer]] {{USS|Daylight|1859|6}} ({{navy|United States|1861}}). She then was wrecked by [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] gunfire, taking 20 to 25 shell hits.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJanJun1863/><ref name=gainesp132>Gaines, p. 132.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==22 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=22 January 1863|sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Congress''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground off [[Seacombe]], [[Cheshire]]. She was on a voyage from [[Maryport]], [[Cumberland]] to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]].<ref name=Times230163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Corris Ann''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: During a voyage from [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], to [[Matanzas]], [[Captaincy General of Cuba|Cuba]], the [[brig]] was captured and burned in the [[Caribbean Sea]] near [[C\u00e1rdenas, Cuba]], between [[Cay Piedras]] and [[Cay Mono]] by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Florida (cruiser)|CSS ''Florida'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America|1861}}). While burning, she drifted ashore inside the harbor at C\u00e1rdenas.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJanJun1863/><ref name=