ountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the [[North Sea]]. She was on a voyage from [[London]] to [[South Shields]], [[County Durham]]. She subsequently came ashore near [[Ringk\u00f8bing]], Denmark. She was later refloated, and sailed for an English port on 31 May.<ref name=Times080663>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=8 June 1863 |page_number=11 |issue=24579 |column=B }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Forward''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the North Sea {{convert|40|nmi|km}} off [[Sunderland, County Durham]]. Her crew were rescued by ''Elizabeth'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=Times310163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mooresfoot''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on Mauritius with the loss of 30 lives.<ref name=Times270263/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''St. George''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foudered in the North Sea. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[London]].<ref name=Times270163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==25 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=25 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Figaro''\n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The ship capsized off [[Margate]], [[Kent]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Cannes]], [[Alpes-Maritimes]] to [[London]], United Kingdom. She was towed in to Margate and righted.<ref name=Times270163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==26 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=26 January 1863|sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item<!--Duke of Lancaster not a loss-->\n|ship=''Gipsy''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship founderedin the [[North Sea]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[London]].<ref name=Times270163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Golden Rule''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[CSS Alabama's Gulf of Mexico Expeditionary Raid]]: The 255-ton [[barque]], carrying a cargo of food and medicine [[Consignment|consigned]] to the [[Panama Railway Company]] and the [[Pacific Mail Steamship Company]] and a full set of [[sail]]s and [[Spar (sailing)|spars]] for the [[brig]] {{USS|Bainbridge|1842|6}} ({{navy|United States|1861}}), was captured and burned in the [[Caribbean Sea]] off Haiti by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Alabama|CSS ''Alabama'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America|1861}}).<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJanJun1863/><ref name=macslogalabama>[http://ahoy.tk-jk.net/MaraudersCivilWar/CSSAlabama.html Ahoy - Mac's Web Log \"Marauders of the Sea, Confederate Merchant Raiders During the American Civil War: CSS Alabama. 1862-1864. Captain Raphael Semmes\"]</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==27 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=27 January 1863|sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Burmah|1858|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] was driven ashore and wrecked near [[Pulicat]], [[British Raj|India]]. All on board were rescued.<ref name=Times180263/><ref name=Times090363>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=India |date=9 March 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24501 |column=E }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Chastelain''<br>(or&nbsp;''Chastelaine'')\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[CSS Alabama's Gulf of Mexico Expeditionary Raid]]: The 293-ton [[brig]], on a voyage in ballast from [[Cienfuegos]], [[Captaincy General of Cuba|Cuba]], to [[Basse-Terre]], [[Guadeloupe]], was captured and burned in the [[Caribbean Sea]] south of [[Hispaniola]] about {{convert|5|nmi|km}} south of [[Alto Velo Island]] ({{coord|17|19|50|N|72|21|00|W|name=''Chastelain''}}) by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Alabama|CSS ''Alabama'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America|1861}}).<ref na