 of the [[Humboldt Bay]] [[Shoal|Bar]].<ref name=gainesp24>Gaines, p. 24.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Elizabeth''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: The [[sloop]], a [[Blockade runners of the American Civil War|blockade runner]] carrying a cargo of [[salt]], was captured and burned at the mouth of [[Jupiter Inlet]] on the coast of [[Florida]], Confederate States of America by the [[gunboat]] {{USS|Sagamore|1861|6}} ({{navy|United States|1861}}).<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJanJun1863/><ref name=gainesp39>Gaines, p. 39.</ref> \n}}<!--Little Dorrit not a loss-->\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary Ann''\n|flag=Flag unknown\n|desc=The [[schooner]]-rigged [[Steamship|steamer]] was wrecked on the coast of [[California]] {{convert|1.5|nmi|km}} south of the Humboldt Bay Bar. She was refloated on 29 June.<ref name=gainesp29>Gaines, p. 29.</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Victory''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship collided with ''Brownfield'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and foundered in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[East Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]].<ref name=Times290163a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==29 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=29 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ceres''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship collided with ''Thomas'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) in the [[Bristol Channel]] and was abandoned by her crew. They were rescued by a Norwegian vessel. ''Ceres'' was on a voyage from [[Lydney]], [[Gloucestershire]] to [[Wick, Caithness|Wick]], [[Caithness]]. She was towed in to [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]] in a derelict condtion.<ref name=Times310163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Empress''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the Ooster Bank, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Zeeland]], Netherlands. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=Times310163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Japhet''\n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on [[Texel]], [[North Holland]], Netherlands. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Blyth, Northumberland]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kindom]] to [[Abbeville]], [[Somme (department)|Somme]].<ref name=Times310163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==30 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=30 January 1863|sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''George Sand''\n|flag=Flag unknown\n|desc=Carrying [[USD|US$]]13,000,000 in [[gold]] and [[silver]] bars and [[Coin|specie]] from [[California]], the [[barque]] foundered in {{convert|360|ft|m}} of water on the [[Praetus Shoals]] in the [[South China Sea]] {{convert|180|nmi|km}} southwest of [[Hong Kong]], [[qing dynasty|China]].<ref>[http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?139560 wrecksite.eu SV George Sand (+1863)]</ref><ref name=gainesp35>Gaines, p. 35.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Isaac Smith||6}}\n|flag={{navy|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The [[screw steamer]] ran aground under fire from [[Confederate States Army]] troops on the [[Stono River]] above [[Legareville, South Carolina]], [[Confederate States of America]], and was captured by the Confederates.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJanJun1863/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n<!--\n==31 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=31 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}-->\n\n==Unknown date==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=Unknown date in Janary 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Amy Louise'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Sunk Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Essex]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was refloated and assisted in to [[Harwich]], Essex by the [[smack (ship)|smack]] ''Queen'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}.<ref name=Benham/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''August'' \n|flag=[[File:POL Szczecin flag.svg|22px]] [[Stettin]] \n|desc=The [[barque]] was run into off Harwich. She was assisted in to Harwich by the [[smack (ship)|smack]] ''Snowdrop'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=Benham>{{cite book |title=The Salvagers |first=Hervey |last=Benham |authorlink=Hervey Benham |pages=11, 189 |publisher=Essex County Newspapers Ltd |location=Colchester |year=1980 |isbn=00 950944 2 3}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Challenge'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore near [[Weymouth, Dorset]] in a derelict condition before 11 January.<ref name=S130163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Danzig \n|flag=Flag unknown\n|desc=The [[barque]] was partly abandoned off the Sunk Sand. Four of her crew got aboard the ''[[Sunk Lightship]]'' ([[File:Trinity House Ensign (pre-1937).svg|22px]] [[Trinity House]] ). ''Danzig'' was assisted in to Harwich by the [[smack (ship)|smack]] ''Afred'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=Benham/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Fidelity'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] foundered off [[Texel]], [[North Holland]], Netherlands before 5 January. She was on a voyage from [[South Shields]], [[County Durham]] to [[London]].<ref name=S100163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Four Brodre'' \n|flag={{flag|Denmark}}\n|desc=The ship sank off [[Far\u00f8]]. She was on a voyage from an English port to \"Croskjobing\".<ref name=LM190163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Haabet'' \n|flag={{flag|Norway|1844}}\n|desc=The ship was lost on the \"Jaddin\". She was on a voyage from [[Colberg]] to [[Bergen]].<ref name=LM190163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Harold''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] before 6 January. Her crew were rescued by ''Express'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Harold'' was on a voyage from [[New York City|New York]], United States to [[Queenstown, County Cork]].<ref name=Times200163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Heinrich Sorensen'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|Russian Empire}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Breaksea Point]], [[Glamorgan]], United Kingdom. Her twelve crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Bordeaux]], [[Gironde]], France to [[Cardiff]], Glamorgan.<ref name=BC>{{cite web |url=http://www.swanseadocks.co.uk/Gower%20wrecks%20Rons%20write-up%20site.pdf |title=A Chronology of Bristol Channel Shipwrecks |first=Ron |last=Tovey |publisher=Swansea Docks |accessdate=19 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222065415/http://www.swanseadocks.co.uk/Gower%20wrecks%20Rons%20write-up%20site.pdf |archivedate=22 December 2014 }}</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Major'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked near [[Belize City]], [[British Honduras]] before 13 January. She was on a voyage from London to Belize City.<ref name=LM150163>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=15 January 1863 |issue=4659 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Marie Amelia'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[brigantine]] was wrecked on the Longsand, in the North Sea off the coast of Essex with the loss of two of her five crew. Survivors were rescued by the [[smack (ship)|smack]] ''Scout'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=Benham/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Nina''\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States of America|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: The 338-bulk ton sidewheel [[paddle steamer]], a [[Blockade runners of the American Civil War|blockade runner]], foundered in the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] between [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]] and [[Charleston, South Carolina]] in late January.<ref name=gainesp15>Gaines, p. 15.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Noonday''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The 2,000-ton [[clipper]] sank in {{convert|240|ft|m}}) of water within an hour of striking Fanny Rock \u2013 subsequently renamed Noonday Rock \u2013 in the [[Farallon Islands]] off the coast of [[California]], [[Confederate States of America]] on 1 or 2 January. The [[pilot boat]] ''Relief'' ({{flag|United States|1861}}) rescued her crew.<ref name=gainesp29/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ocean Gem''\n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[British North America]]\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the Atlantic Ocean. Her crew were rescued by ''National'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=Times260163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=26 January 1863 |page_number=8 |issue=24465 |column=C-D }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pamela Flood''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] foundered with the loss of all but her captain. She was on a voyage from [[New Orleans, Louisiana]], [[Confederate States of America]] to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]], United Kingdom.<ref name=Times230163a>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=23 January 1863 |page_number=11 |issue=24463 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Shah Allum''\n|flag=[[file:Flag of the British East India Company (1801).svg|22px]] [[British Raj|India]]\n|desc=The ship was reported missing. She was on a voyage from [[Calcutta]] to [[Mauritius]].<ref name=Times270263/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Victoria'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was abandoned off [[Aldeburgh]], [[Suffolk]]. She was subsequently assisted in to [[Lowestoft]] Suffolk.<ref name=Benham2>{{cite book |title=The Salvagers |first=Hervey |last=Benham |authorlink=Hervey Benham |page=189 |publisher=Essex County Newspapers Ltd |location=Colchester |year=1980 |isbn=00 950944 2 3}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unidentified sloop\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States of America|1861}}\n|desc=The [[sloop]] was wrecked in [[Kings Creek (West Virginia)|King's Creek]] in [[Virginia]].<ref name=gainesp193/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* [http://scubagonewild.com/documents/Encyclopedia%20of%20Civil%20War%20Shipwrecks%20-%20(Malestrom).pdf Gaines, W. Craig, ''Encyclopedia of Civil War Shipwrecks'', Louisiana State University Press, 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-8071-3274-6}}.]\n* Ingram, C. W. N., and Wheatley, P. O., (1936) ''Shipwrecks: New Zealand disasters 1795\u20131936.'' Dunedin, NZ: Dunedin Book Publishing Association.\n\n{{shipevents|1863}}\n{{1860s shipwrecks}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of shipwrecks by year|1863-01]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in January 1863| Shipwrecks01]]\n<!--\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''xxxx'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship .<ref name=0163>{{Cite news |title= |newspaper= |location= |date= January 1863 |issue= }}</ref>\n}}\n-->\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe '''list of shipwrecks in January 1863''' includes ships sunk, foundered, grounded, or otherwise lost during January [[1863]].\n{{Dynamic list}}\n{{Calendar ToC}}\n\n==1 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=1 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Carmen''\n|flag={{flag|Chile}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] foundered in the [[Pacific Ocean]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Coquimbo]] to [[Lota, Chile|Lota]].<ref name=Times020363a>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The West India, Pacific, and Mexican Mails |date=2 March 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24495 |column=C-D }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[CS Neptune|CS ''Neptune'']] (or&nbsp;CSS&nbsp;''Neptune Camp'')\n|flag={{army|Confederate States of America|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Battle of Galveston]]: The armed [[cottonclad]] [[Tugboat|tug]] was sunk by [[United States Navy]] warships in Galveston Harbor off [[Galveston, Texas]], when a shell passed through her [[Hull (ship)|hull]]. She suffered eight killed and 20 wounded, and three of the wounded later died of their injuries.<ref name=gainesp171>Gaines, p. 171.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Nova Scotian''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Colombo]], [[Ceylon]]. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=Times050163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Westfield|1861|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War, Battle of Galvesto]: The armed sidewheel [[paddle steamer]], serving as [[flagship]] of the naval squadron [[Union blockade|blockading]] Galveston, ran aground on a [[sandbar]] in Galveston Harbor off Galveston, while in action with the [[gunboat]] [[CS Bayou City|CS ''Bayou City'']] and the armed [[tugboat]] [[CS Neptune|CS ''Neptune'']] (both {{army|Confederate States of America|1861}}). She was blown up to prevent her capture by [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] forces, killing the fleet commander, [[Commander (United States)|Commander]] [[William B. Renshaw]], and several members of her crew when the explosives detonated sooner than they expected.<ref name=\"gainesp172\">Gaines, p. 172.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==2 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=2 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Arnoldi'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[cutter (ship)|cutter]] ran aground on the Middle Sand, off the north [[Kent]] coast. She was refloated and towed in to [[Whitstable]] in a severely leaky condition.<ref name=LM050163>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=5 January 1863 |issue=4650 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Gratitude'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on the Newcombe Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Suffolk]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=S050163>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=5 January 1863 |issue=11981 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Louisa''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Braunton]], [[Devon]] with the loss of one of her eight crew. Survivors were rescued by the Braunton Lifeboat. She was on a voyage from [[Appledore, Torridge|Appledore]], Devon to [[Newport, Monmouthshire]].<ref name=Times030163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=3 January 1863 |page_number=9 |issue=24446 |column=B }}</ref><ref name=Times050163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=5 January 1863 |page_number=11 |issue=24447 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Marie Amelie''\n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the Longsand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Essex]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] with the loss of three of her crew. She was on a voyage from [[Grimsby]], [[Lincolnshire]], United Kingdom to [[Bordeaux]], [[Gironde]].<ref name=Times050163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ripple'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore near [[Chipiona]], Spain. She was on a voyage from [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]] to [[Seville]], Spain. She was refloated the next day and taken in to Seville, where she was condemned.<ref name=S100163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Dantsic''\n|flag=[[File:Gdansk flag.svg|22px]] [[Danzig|Dantsic]] \n|desc=The ship foundered in the [[North Sea]]. All five people on board were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[London]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] to Dantsic.<ref name=Times080163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Neuha'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[ketch]] ran aground on the Abertay Bank, at the mouth of the [[River Tay]] and sank. Her crew were rescued by the Broughty Ferry and Buddonness Lifeboats. She was on a voyage from [[North Shields]], [[Northumberland]] to [[Dundee]], [[Forfarshire]].<ref name=DC050163>{{Cite news |title=Vessel Wrecked in the River |newspaper=Dundee Courier |location=Dundee |date=5 January 1863 |issue=2934 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Time and Truth''\n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[Victoria (Australia)]]\n|desc=The [[barque]] carrying 2,600 sheep, was approaching [[Bluff, New Zealand|Bluff]], New Zealand from Melbourne when a heavy gale sprang up. The captain attempted to take the ship into Bluff Harbour, but it was struck by a swell and pushed into rocks off [[Stirling Point]]. The [[steamship|steamer]] ''Aphrasis'' succeeding in rescuing the crew and about 500 sheep before the ''Time and Truth'' went under. While returning to Bluff, the ''Aphrasis'' herself was involved in a collision with the steamer ''Prince Alfred'' and was heavily damaged.<ref name=SNZD8384>Ingram & Wheatley, pp. 83\u201384.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lady Mary Stewart'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship struck the Garrick Rock, in the [[Irish Sea]]. She was on a voyage from [[Runcorn]], [[Cheshire]] to [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]]. She put in to [[Port St. Mary]], [[Isle of Man]] in a leaky condition.<ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pax'' \n|flag={{flag|Hamburg|admiralty}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore near \"Kjaergaard\", Denmark. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Rostock]] to [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]].<ref name=S100163/><ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==5 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=5 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Iceni''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was destroyed by fire at sea. Her crew were rescued by ''Yorkshire'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=Times230163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Prosperity'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[sloop]] ran aground on the Longsand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Essex]]. She was on a voyage from [[Dunkerque]], [[Nord (departements)|Nord]] to [[London]]. She was refloated and assisted in to [[Harwich]], Essed.<ref name=Benham/><ref name=S080163>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=8 January 1863 |issue=11984 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==6 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Balmoral'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground off Whiteforeland Point, [[Renfrewshire]]. She was on a voyage from [[Glasgow]], Renfrewshire to the [[West Indies]]. She was refloated and towed back to Glasgow.<ref name=S130163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Batallion'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] was driven ashore at [[Sunderland, County Durham]]. She was on a voyage from [[Bordeaux]], [[Gironde]] to Sunderland. She was refloated and taken in to port.<ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Esteburg'' \n|flag={{flag|Hamburg|admiralty}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Eyemouth]], [[Berwickshire]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was on a voyage from [[Rye, Sussex]] to [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]], United Kingdom. She was refloated and taken in to Eyemouth in a severely damaged condition.<ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jacob Musselman''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The 144-ton [[Paddle steamer|sternwheel]] [[Troop transport|transport]] was captured by troops of the [[Arkansas Cavalry Company]] ({{army|Confederate States of America|1861}}) on the [[Mississippi River]] opposite [[Memphis, Tennessee]], [[Confederate States of America]]. The [[Confederate States Army]] took her 15 miles (24 km) upstream to [[Bradley's Landing]], [[Arkansas]], where they removed her cargo and burned her.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJanJun1863>[http://www.usnlp.org/navychronology/1863a.html usnlp.org Navy Chronology of the Civil War, January-June 1863]</ref><ref name=gainesp97>Gaines, p. 97.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sally'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] ran around and was wrecked at [[Bilbao|Bilboa]], Spain. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to Bilboa.<ref name=S140163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unidentified flatboat\n|flag=Unknown\n|desc=American Civil War: The [[flatboat]] was burned by Confederate States Army forces at Bradley's Landing.<ref name=gainesp97/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==7 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=7 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''La Plata'', and<br>''Liverpool''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] ''La Plata'' and the [[steamship]] ''Liverpool'' collided off [[Point Lynas]], [[Anglesey]]. Both vessels sank. ''La Plata'' was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Lima]], Peru. Her crew reached [[Holyhead]], Anglesey in their boats. ''Liverpool'' was on a voyage from [[London]] to Liverpool. Her crew were rescued by the steamship ''Athlete'' and the [[tugboat|tug]] ''Cruiser'' (both {{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=Times080163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=8 January 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24450 |column=E }}</ref><ref name=Times090163>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Collision off Holyhead |date=9 January 1863 |page_number=3 |issue=24451 |column=D }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Little Magruder''\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States of America|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The [[Steamship|steamer]] was destroyed on the [[Pamunkey River]] at [[White House, Virginia]], by an expedition consisting of the armed sidewheel [[paddle steamer]] {{USS|Mahaska|1861|6}} and the [[gunboat]] {{USS|Commodore Perry}} (both {{navy|United States|1861}}), the [[Tugboat|tug]] ''May Queen'' ({{flag|United States|1861|name=United States Army}}), and troops of the [[5th Pennsylvania Cavalry Regiment]], [[6th New York Cavalry Regiment]], and [[115th New York Infantry Regiment]] (all {{flag|United States|1861|name=Union Army}}).<ref name=gainesp184/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Nepenthe''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on [[Santo Ant\u00e3o, Cape Verde|Santo Ant\u00e3o]], [[Cape Verde Islands]]. All on board were rescued. She was on a voyage from Liverpool to [[Calcutta]], [[British Raj|India]].<ref name=Times190163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Robert''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] collided with another vessel and was abandoned by her crew. She was subsequently taken in to [[Ramsgate]], [[Kent]].<ref name=Times080163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unidentified vessels\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States of America|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War: A [[ferryboat]], two [[sloop]]s, a large [[scow]], two [[barge]]s, and four [[pontoon boat]]s were destroyed on the Pamunkey River at White House, Virginia, by an expedition consisting of the armed sidewheel [[paddle steamer]] {{USS|Mahaska|1861|6}} and the [[gunboat]] {{USS|Commodore Perry}} (both {{navy|United States|1861}}), the [[Tugboat|tug]] ''May Queen'' ({{flag|United States|1861|name=United States Army}}), and troops of the [[5th Pennsylvania Cavalry Regiment]], 6th New York Cavalry Regiment, and 115th New York Infantry Regiment (all {{flag|United States|1861|name=Union Army}}).<ref name=gainesp193>Gaines, p. 193.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==8 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=8 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Barmouth''\n