ivil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on the Holm Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Suffolk]]. She was on a voyage from [[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]] to [[Sunderland, County Durham]]. She was refloated and taken in to [[Lowestoft]], Suffolk.<ref name=S140163/><ref name=NC160163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pelican'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] was driven ashore at [[Waterloo, Lancashire]]. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Cork (city)|Cork]].<ref name=S140163/> She was later refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=LM160163>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=16 January 1863 |issue=4660 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Trio''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War: Carrying 400 wounded [[Union Army]] troops and a cargo of [[cotton]], the 150-ton [[Paddle steamer|sternwheel]] [[Hospital ship|hospital steamer]] was captured and burned by troops of the [[cavalry]] [[brigade]] of [[Major general|Major General]] [[Joseph Wheeler]] ({{army|Confederate States of America|1863}}) on the [[Nashville, Tennessee]], [[Confederate States of America]], side of the [[Cumberland River]] {{convert|5|nmi|km}} from [[Harpeth Shoals]].<ref name=gainesp162>Gaines, p. 162.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''W. H. Slidell''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War: The armed [[tinclad]] [[Steamship|steamer]] was captured and burned by troops of the [[cavalry]] [[brigade]] of [[Major general|Major General]] [[Joseph Wheeler]] ({{army|Confederate States of America|1863}}) on the Nashville side of the Cumberland River {{convert|5|nmi|km}} from Harpeth Shoals.<ref name=gainesp164>Gaines, p. 164.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==14 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=14 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Columbia|1862|6}}\n|flag={{navy|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: The armed [[screw steamer]] ran aground at [[Masonboro Inlet]], [[North Carolina]], [[Confederate States of America]]. After a [[gale]] struck on 15 January, the gunboat {{USS|Penobscot|1861|6}} ({{navy|United States|1861}}) rescued 30 men from the wreck during the storm on 15\u201316 January before Confederate [[artillery]] drove her off. Confederate forces captured the wreck on 17 January and burned it.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJanJun1863/><ref name=Gainesp116>Gaines, p.116</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Earl of Derby'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship caught fire in [[Lough Foyle]] and was scuttled.<ref name=LM150163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Parthonia''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War: The 261-ton sternwheel [[paddle steamer]] was burned by [[Confederate States Army]] troops on the [[Cumberland River]] in [[Tennessee]], Confederate States of America. They had captured her on the river the previous day at the head of [[Harpeth Shoals]].<ref name=gainesp162>Gaines, p. 162.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pioneer''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on a reef off the Karren Islands, [[Netherlands East Indies]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Manila]], [[Spanish East Indies]] to [[London]].<ref name=Times180263>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=18 February 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24485 |column=A }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rose'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was wrecked on the Villez Martin Rocks, on the coast of [[Loire-Inf\u00e9rieure]]. She was on a voyage from [[Dunkerque]], [[Nord (departements)|Nord]] to [[Nantes]], Loire-Inf\u00e9rieure.<ref name=S200163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==15 January==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=15 January 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Dashaway''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore {{convert|20|nmi|km}} north east of [[Cape May]], [[New Jersey]]. She was on a voyage from [[Messina]], [[Sicily]], [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]] to [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=Times040263>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=4 February 1863 |page_number=5 |issue=24473 |column=E }}</ref>\n}}<!--Enterprise not ashore at Mockbeggar on this date-->\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Iron Duke'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] was driven ashore at [[Mockbeggar, Cheshire]].<ref name=LM200163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[CSS J. A. Cotton|CSS ''J. A. Cotton'']]\n|flag={{navy|Confederate States of America|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The [[Paddle steamer|sidewheel]] partial [[Ironclad warship|ironclad]] [[gunboat]] was [[Scuttling|scuttled]] and burned by her crew in [[Bayou Teche]] off [[Brashear City, Louisiana|Brashear City]], [[Louisiana]], to serve as a [[blockship]] and to prevent her capture by [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] forces after she was badly damaged in combat with [[United States Navy]] gunboats.<ref>[https://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/confederate_ships/j-a-cotton.html Naval History and Heritage Command: Confederate Ships: J. A. Cotton]</ref><ref name=gainesp67>Gaines, p. 67.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''M\u00e8re de Famille''\n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The ship was run down and sunk in the [[English Channel]] off [[Portland Dorset]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] by ''Turk'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). Her crew were rescued by ''Turk''.<ref name=Times190163/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rosebud'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the Barrow Sand, in the North Sea off the coast of Essex. Her five crew were rescued by the [[smack (ship)|smack]] ''Alarm'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Rosebud'' was on a voyage fro